1. Loading the data

First I extracted the data from https://data.stackexchange.com/stackoverflow/query/new https://data.stackexchange.com/stackoverflow/query/edit/1737869

I have used these command line for extraction where I specified that we need questions (PostTypeId = 1),
with a score bigger than 4 and view count bigger than 100 while the question received at least 1 answer
and that the questions contain at least 5 tags:

SELECT TOP 500000 Id, Title, Body, Tags, Score, ViewCount, AnswerCount
FROM Posts
WHERE PostTypeId = 1 AND Score > 4 AND ViewCount > 100
AND AnswerCount > 0 AND (LEN(Tags) - LEN(REPLACE(Tags, '<', ''))) >= 5

# Function to add infos about the type and null values to .describe function
def df_description(df):
    # General description
    description = df.describe(include='all', datetime_is_numeric=True)

    # Types and content of the columns
    description_type = pd.DataFrame(df.dtypes, columns=['type']).T
    number_null = (df.shape[0] - description.loc['count'].T)
    percent_null = (df.shape[0] - description.loc['count'].T)*100/df.shape[0]
    description_null = pd.DataFrame([number_null, percent_null],
                                    index=['number null', 'percentage null'])

    # Concatenate general, type and null stats
    description = pd.concat([description_type, description_null, description])
    return description

# Function that generate a df containing all the words and their frequency
def words_freq_fct(df, column, freq_min):
    words = Counter(word for x in df[column].str.split() for word in set(x))
    words_df = pd.DataFrame()
    words_df[['Word', 'Frequency']] = words.keys(), words.values()
    words_df.sort_values('Frequency', ascending=False, inplace=True)
    print('Number of unique words in {} = {}, while {} words appeared only in {} questions or less.'
          .format(column,
                  words_df.shape[0],
                  words_df[words_df['Frequency'] <= freq_min].shape[0],
                  freq_min))
    words_df = words_df.reset_index(drop=True)
    return words_df

# Function that remove the questions length lower than an input parameter length
def length_limit(df, column, length):
    cond = df[df[column] <= length]
    print('The number of questions with {} length of {} or less = {}'
          .format(column, length, cond.shape[0]))
    df.drop(cond.index, inplace=True)
    print('After removing those questions, we are left with this number of rows:',
          df.shape[0])

    # Resetting the index after the cleaning
    df = df.reset_index(drop=True)
    
    return df

def tag_iteration_cleaning(df, column, rare_limit, len_limit):
    # Remove the rare words that appeared less than rare_limit times in tags
    c = Counter(word for x in df[column].str.split() for word in set(x))
    new_tags_col = column + '_' + str(rare_limit)
    df[new_tags_col] = [' '.join(y for y in x if c[y] >= rare_limit)
                        for x in df[column].str.split()]
    # Creating a columns indicating the length of Tags
    length_col = 'length_' + new_tags_col
    df[length_col] = df[new_tags_col].apply(lambda x: len(x.split(' ')))
    # Removing questions with less than len_limit tags
    df = length_limit(df, length_col, len_limit)
    return df

# Function that will be used for removing the a href links and code tags
def href_code_removing(x):
    BS = BeautifulSoup(x, 'lxml')
    for link in BS.find_all(['a', 'code', 'blockquote']):
        link.decompose()
    return BS.get_text()

    SO_questions_df.loc[i, 'Body_filt'] = re.sub(r'http\S+', '',
                                                 SO_questions_df.loc[i, 'Body_filt'],
                                                 flags=re.MULTILINE)
    # Remove English contractions
    SO_questions_df.loc[i, 'Title_filt'] = re.sub("\'\w+", '',
                                                  SO_questions_df.loc[i, 'Title_filt'],
                                                  flags=re.MULTILINE)
    SO_questions_df.loc[i, 'Body_filt'] = re.sub("\'\w+", '',
                                                 SO_questions_df.loc[i, 'Body_filt'],
                                                 flags=re.MULTILINE)
    # Remove adverbs (ly)
    SO_questions_df.loc[i, 'Title_filt'] = re.sub(r"\w+ly\b", '',
                                                  SO_questions_df.loc[i, 'Title_filt'],
                                                  flags=re.MULTILINE)
    SO_questions_df.loc[i, 'Body_filt'] = re.sub(r"\w+ly\b", '',
                                                 SO_questions_df.loc[i, 'Body_filt'],

def start_end_char_clean(df, column, Tags):
    # Removing all folder link like c:\ or c:/ etc
    texts = list(df[column])
    c = set(word for x in texts for word in x.split(' ')
            if ((word.startswith("a:") or word.startswith("b:")
                 or word.startswith("c:") or word.startswith("d:")
                 or word.startswith("e:") or word.startswith("f:")
                 or word.startswith("g:") or word.startswith("h:")
                 or word.startswith("file:")
                 or word.startswith(":\\") or word.startswith(":/")
                 or word.startswith("\\") or word.endswith("\\")
                 or word.startswith("/") or word.endswith("/")
                 or word.startswith("./") or word.endswith("/.")
                 or word.startswith("<") or word.endswith(">")
                 or word.startswith("[") or word.endswith("]")
                 or word.startswith("{") or word.endswith("}")
                 or word.startswith("-") or word.endswith("-")
                 or word.startswith("+") or word.startswith("$"))
                and word not in Tags))
    df[column] = [' '.join(y for y in x.split() if y not in c) for x in texts]
    return df[column]

We will be using RegexpTokenizer instead of word_tokenize for tokenizing the title and body.

  • First we will tokenize the sentences.
  • Second we will filter out the stopwords, adjective and adverbs.
  • Third we will Lemmatize or Stem the words.
  • Fourth we will clean the sentences from rare words appearing only few times

# Function that tokenize sentences
def tokenizer_fct(sentence) :
    sentence_clean = sentence.replace('---', '').replace('--', '')\
                             .replace('- ', ' ').replace(' -', ' ')\
                             .replace('...', '').replace('..', '')\
                             .replace('. ', ' ')\
                             .replace('_ ', ' ').replace(' _', ' ')\
                             .replace(' &', ' ').replace('& ', ' ')\
                             .replace('^', ' ')\
                             .replace('?', '').replace('!', '')\
                             .replace(';', ' ').replace(',', ' ')\
                             .replace("'", ' ').replace('"', ' ')\
                             .replace("’", ' ').replace('=', ' ')\
                             .replace(')', ' ').replace('(', ' ')\
                             .replace('|', ' ')\
                             .replace('% ', ' ').replace(' %', ' ')\
                             .replace(' #', ' ').replace('@', ' ')\
                             .replace('*', ' ')\
                             .replace('`', ' ').replace('~', ' ')
    tokenizer = RegexpTokenizer(r'\S+')
    word_tokens = tokenizer.tokenize(sentence_clean)
    return word_tokens


# Stop word filtering
def stop_word_filter_fct(list_words) :
    word_tokens = tokenizer_fct(list_words)
    # Removing all digits and stop words
    filtered_w = [w for w in word_tokens if (not w.isdigit() and not w in stop_w)]
    return filtered_w


# Adjective and adverbe filtering
def adj_adv_word_filter_fct(list_words) :
    word_tokens = stop_word_filter_fct(list_words)
    # Tags of adjective and adverbs
    adj_adv_tags = ['JJR', 'JJS', 'RB', 'RBR', 'RBS', 'WRB']
    # Tagging the words
    tags = dict(pos_tag(word_tokens))
    # Selecting the words tagged adjective and adverbs and not in tags list
    adj_adv_words = [word for word,pos in tags.items() if (pos in adj_adv_tags
                                                           and word not in list(Tag_words_df['Word']))]
    # Removing those words
    filtered_w = [w for w in word_tokens if not w in adj_adv_words]
    return filtered_w

# Lemmatizer
def lem_fct(list_words) :
    lemmatizer = WordNetLemmatizer()
    lem_w = [lemmatizer.lemmatize(w) for w in list_words]
    final_w = ' '.join(lem_w)
    return final_w


# Stemmer
def stem_fct(list_words) :
    stemmer = PorterStemmer()
    stem_w = [stemmer.stem(w) for w in list_words]
    final_w = ' '.join(stem_w)
    return final_w

# Function that correct the length of a specific column and remove all questions with no words
def cleaning_0_length(df, column, length_column):
    
    # Correcting the length of title and body with 0 when the == ''
    index_for_0 = df[df[column] == ''].index
    df.loc[index_for_0, length_column] = df.loc[index_for_0, length_column].replace(1, 0)
    print('Number of questions with 0 length =', df[df[length_column] == 0].shape[0])
    
    # Dropping those questions
    df.drop(index_for_0, inplace=True)
    print('After removing those questions, we are left with these number of rows:', df.shape[0])
    return df

def title_body_iteration_cleaning(df, column, col_1, col_2, rare_limit, len_limit):
    # Remove the rare words that appeared less than rare_limit times in title_body
    c = Counter(word for x in df[column].str.split() for word in set(x))
    df[column] = [' '.join(y for y in x if (c[y] >= rare_limit))
                  for x in df[column].str.split()]
    df[col_1] = [' '.join(y for y in x if (c[y] >= rare_limit))
                 for x in df[col_1].str.split()]
    df[col_2] = [' '.join(y for y in x if (c[y] >= rare_limit))
                 for x in df[col_2].str.split()]
    # Creating a columns indicating the length of column
    length_col = 'length_' + column
    df[length_col] = df[column].apply(lambda x: len(x.split(' ')))
    # Removing questions with less than len_limit words
    df = length_limit(df, length_col, len_limit)
    return df

# Function that create bigram and trigram
def bi_trigram_formation(df, column):
    # A way to have a list of words for each sentence from title_body_filt_lem
    X_sample = list(df[column].str.split())

    # Build the bigram and trigram models (higher threshold fewer phrases)
    bigram = gensim.models.Phrases(X_sample, min_count=30, threshold=300)
    trigram = gensim.models.Phrases(bigram[X_sample], threshold=300)  

    # Faster way to get a sentence clubbed as a trigram/bigram
    bigram_mod = gensim.models.phrases.Phraser(bigram)
    trigram_mod = gensim.models.phrases.Phraser(trigram)

    def make_bigrams(texts):
        return [bigram_mod[doc] for doc in texts]

    def make_trigrams(texts):
        return [trigram_mod[bigram_mod[doc]] for doc in texts]

    # Form Bigrams
    X_sample_bigrams = make_bigrams(X_sample)
    X_sample_bigrams_trigrams = make_trigrams(X_sample_bigrams)

    # Saving to df
    df[column + '_bitri'] = [' '.join(x) for x in X_sample_bigrams_trigrams]
    
    return df

# Load the stop_words
stop_w = joblib.load('data/stop_w.pkl')


# Function that take the title and body of a question and perform
# filtering, tokenization, lemmatization or stemming
def filter_tokenize_lem_stem(question_title, question_body):

    start = time.time()

    # Creating a varaible containing both the title and body
    question_title_body = question_title + ' ' + question_body

    # lower case the texts
    question_title_body = ' '.join([x.lower().replace('\n', ' ') for x in question_title_body.split()])

    # Function that will be used for removing the a href links and code tags
    def href_code_removing(x):
        BS = BeautifulSoup(x, 'lxml')
        for link in BS.find_all(['a', 'code', 'blockquote']):
            link.decompose()
        return BS.get_text()

    question_title_body_filt = ' '.join([href_code_removing(x) for x in question_title_body.split()])


    # Removing the links without a href in body and title
    question_title_body_filt = re.sub(r'http\S+', '', question_title_body, flags=re.MULTILINE)
    # Remove English contractions
    question_title_body_filt = re.sub("\'\w+", '', question_title_body_filt, flags=re.MULTILINE)
    # Remove adverbs (ly)
    question_title_body_filt = re.sub(r"\w+ly\b", '', question_title_body_filt, flags=re.MULTILINE)
    # Remove string of pure float numbers and remove . at the end of string
    question_title_body_filt = re.sub("((?<=[a-zA-Z:])+\.+?)|((?<=[\s])+?(\d*\.*)*)", ' ',
                                      question_title_body_filt, flags=re.MULTILINE)


    def start_end_char_clean(texts):
        # Removing all folder link like c:\ or c:/ etc
        c = set(word for x in texts for word in x
                if ((word.startswith("a:") or word.startswith("b:")
                     or word.startswith("c:") or word.startswith("d:")
                     or word.startswith("e:") or word.startswith("f:")
                     or word.startswith("g:") or word.startswith("h:")
                     or word.startswith("file:")
                     or word.startswith(":\\") or word.startswith(":/")
                     or word.startswith("\\") or word.endswith("\\")
                     or word.startswith("/") or word.endswith("/")
                     or word.startswith("./") or word.endswith("/.")
                     or word.startswith("<") or word.endswith(">")
                     or word.startswith("[") or word.endswith("]")
                     or word.startswith("{") or word.endswith("}")
                     or word.startswith("-") or word.endswith("-")
                     or word.startswith("+") or word.startswith("$"))))
        texts = ' '.join(y for y in texts.split() if y not in c)
        return texts

    question_title_body_filt = start_end_char_clean(question_title_body_filt)


    def tokenizer_fct(sentence) :
        sentence_clean = sentence.replace('---', '').replace('--', '')\
                                 .replace('- ', ' ').replace(' -', ' ')\
                                 .replace('...', '').replace('..', '')\
                                 .replace('. ', ' ')\
                                 .replace('_ ', ' ').replace(' _', ' ')\
                                 .replace(' &', ' ').replace('& ', ' ')\
                                 .replace('^', ' ')\
                                 .replace('?', '').replace('!', '')\
                                 .replace(';', ' ').replace(',', ' ')\
                                 .replace("'", ' ').replace('"', ' ')\
                                 .replace("’", ' ').replace('=', ' ')\
                                 .replace(')', ' ').replace('(', ' ')\
                                 .replace('|', ' ')\
                                 .replace('% ', ' ').replace(' %', ' ')\
                                 .replace(' #', ' ').replace('@', ' ')\
                                 .replace('*', ' ')\
                                 .replace('`', ' ').replace('~', ' ')
        tokenizer = RegexpTokenizer(r'\S+')
        word_tokens = tokenizer.tokenize(sentence_clean)
        return word_tokens


    # Stop word filtering
    def stop_word_filter_fct(list_words) :
        word_tokens = tokenizer_fct(list_words)
        # Removing all digits and stop words
        filtered_w = [w for w in word_tokens if (not w.isdigit() and not w in stop_w)]
        return filtered_w


    # Adjective and adverbe filtering
    def adj_adv_word_filter_fct(list_words) :
        word_tokens = stop_word_filter_fct(list_words)
        # Tags of adjective and adverbs
        adj_adv_tags = ['JJR', 'JJS', 'RB', 'RBR', 'RBS', 'WRB']
        # Tagging the words
        tags = dict(pos_tag(word_tokens))
        # Selecting the words tagged adjective and adverbs and not in tags list
        adj_adv_words = [word for word,pos in tags.items() if (pos in adj_adv_tags)]
        # Removing those words
        filtered_w = ' '.join([w for w in word_tokens if not w in adj_adv_words])
        return filtered_w


    print('Text after filtering, and tokenizing:\n{}\n'.format(adj_adv_word_filter_fct(question_title_body_filt)))


    # Lemmatizer
    def lem_fct(list_words) :
        list_words = adj_adv_word_filter_fct(list_words)
        lemmatizer = WordNetLemmatizer()
        lem_w = [lemmatizer.lemmatize(w) for w in list_words.split()]
        final_w = ' '.join(lem_w)
        return final_w


    # Stemmer
    def stem_fct(list_words) :
        list_words = adj_adv_word_filter_fct(list_words)
        stemmer = PorterStemmer()
        stem_w = [stemmer.stem(w) for w in list_words.split()]
        final_w = ' '.join(stem_w)
        return final_w

    question_title_body_filt_lem = lem_fct(question_title_body_filt)
    question_title_body_filt_stem = stem_fct(question_title_body_filt)

    question_title_body_filt_lem = start_end_char_clean(question_title_body_filt_lem)
    question_title_body_filt_stem = start_end_char_clean(question_title_body_filt_stem)


    def final_clean(sentence):
        sentence = sentence.replace(':', '')\
                           .replace('<','').replace('>','')\
                           .replace('[','').replace(']','')\
                           .replace('{','').replace('}','')
        sentence = ' '.join([w for w in sentence.split(' ') if ((len(w) > 2 and not w.isdigit()))])
        return sentence

    question_title_body_filt_lem = final_clean(question_title_body_filt_lem)
    question_title_body_filt_stem = final_clean(question_title_body_filt_stem)

    # Remove the left over string of pure float numbers
    question_title_body_filt_lem = re.sub("((?<=[\s])+?(\d*\.*)*)", '',
                                          question_title_body_filt_lem,
                                          flags=re.MULTILINE)
    question_title_body_filt_stem = re.sub("((?<=[\s])+?(\d*\.*)*)", '',
                                           question_title_body_filt_stem,
                                           flags=re.MULTILINE)

    stop = time.time()
    print('Processing time: {}s\n'.format(np.around((stop-start), 2)))
    print('Text after filtering, tokenizing, and lemmatization:\n{}\n'.format(question_title_body_filt_lem))
    print('Text after filtering, tokenizing, and stemming:\n{}'.format(question_title_body_filt_stem))

    return question_title_body_filt_lem, question_title_body_filt_stem

4. Final conclusion

  • The example given in Sec.3 show how well the filtering is done on a given text.
  • Even so that the stemmer leads to smaller vocabulary, I'm going to use lemmatizer during the modelisation because stemmer can leads to incorrect meanings and spelling of some words.
  • We saw that the title is better suited to extract key-words than the body. However, there are lot of questions title with fewer words than the number of tags (all questions have >=5 tags) which can be problematic to the supervised learning modelisation. Therefore, we will use the title_body during the supervised learning modelisation.
